===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# {{senseid|en|awake}} [[alert|Alert]], [[awake]]; with one's [[mental]] [[faculty|faculties]] active.
#: {{ux|en|The noise woke me, but it was another few minutes before I was fully '''conscious'''.}}
# [[aware|Aware]] of one's own existence; [[aware]] of one's own [[awareness]].
#* '''1999''', Eckhart Tolle, ''The Power of Now'', Hodder and Stoughton, pages 61–62:
#*: The best indicator of your level of consciousness is how you deal with life's challenges when they come.&nbsp; Through those challenges, an already unconscious person tends to become more deeply unconscious, and a '''conscious''' person more intensely '''conscious'''.
#: {{ux|en|Only highly intelligent beings can be fully '''conscious'''.}}
# [[aware|Aware]] of, [[sensitive]] to; observing and noticing, or being strongly interested in or concerned about.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1918|author={{w|W. B. Maxwell}}|chapter=5
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1097634W The Mirror and the Lamp]
|passage=Here, in the transept and choir, where the service was being held, one was '''conscious''' every moment of an increasing brightness; colours glowing vividly beneath the circular chandeliers, and the rows of small lights on the choristers' desks flashed and sparkled in front of the boys' faces, deep linen collars, and red neckbands.}}
#* {{RQ:Orwell Animal Farm|6}}
#*: Once again the animals were '''conscious''' of a vague uneasiness.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1955|author=Arthur Smithies|title=The Budgetary Process in the United States|page=290|passage=Furthermore, the military operator is far less '''conscious''' of budgetary constraints than is the civilian consumer.}}
#: {{ux|en|I was '''conscious''' of a noise behind me. &nbsp; a very class-'''conscious''' analysis}}
# [[deliberate|Deliberate]], [[intentional]], done with [[awareness]] of what one is doing.
#* '''1907''', Brigham Henry Roberts, ''Defense of the Faith and the Saints'', volume 1, page 43:
#*: He candidly confesses that it is an effort to account for Joseph Smith upon some other hypothesis than that he was a '''conscious''' fraud, bent on deceiving mankind.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2015|author=Jamie Kornegay|title=Soil: A Novel|page=214|passage=Start fresh, try and learn from past mistakes, make a '''conscious''' effort to be a better person.}}
# [[known|Known]] or [[felt]] personally, internally by a person.
#: '''''conscious''' guilt''
# <!--dated?--> [[self-conscious|Self-conscious]].
#* '''1616—1650''', Richard Crashaw:
#*: The '''conscious''' water saw its God, and blushed.

